00:11:08.540 --> 00:11:10.840 align:middle line:84%
But I assure you,
laughter is not just

00:11:10.840 --> 00:11:14.020 align:middle line:84%
some airy fairy or
hippy dippy medicine.

00:11:14.020 --> 00:11:18.080 align:middle line:84%
It truly has a measurable
health benefits to it.

00:11:18.080 --> 00:11:22.420 align:middle line:10%
So let's take a little bit
deeper of a look at laughter

00:11:22.420 --> 00:11:24.820 align:middle line:10%
with a film called
"Nature's Medicine,

00:11:24.820 --> 00:11:28.170 align:middle line:10%
from Herbs to Laughter".

00:11:28.170 --> 00:11:31.320 align:middle line:84%
>> Their benefits are not
limited to societal factors,

00:11:31.320 --> 00:11:33.820 align:middle line:84%
as scientists have found
that laughter generates

00:11:33.820 --> 00:11:38.950 align:middle line:84%
physiological changes
that soothe body and mind.

00:11:38.950 --> 00:11:42.220 align:middle line:10%
Some laughs later,
the pulse falls,

00:11:42.220 --> 00:11:44.650 align:middle line:10%
there is a rise in the levels
of happy hormones known

00:11:44.650 --> 00:11:49.960 align:middle line:10%
as endorphins, and more
oxygen reaches the muscles.

00:11:49.960 --> 00:11:52.900 align:middle line:84%
The natural immune power
of the body enhances.

00:11:52.900 --> 00:11:54.820 align:middle line:84%
Besides, the stress
hormones which

00:11:54.820 --> 00:11:56.335 align:middle line:90%
the blood contains diminish.

00:11:56.335 --> 00:12:02.620 align:middle line:90%


00:12:02.620 --> 00:12:07.440 align:middle line:10%
Hence, laughter is
actually beneficial for us.

00:12:07.440 --> 00:12:10.830 align:middle line:84%
But sadly, as adults, we simply
don't have enough laughs.

00:12:10.830 --> 00:12:13.490 align:middle line:90%


00:12:13.490 --> 00:12:17.150 align:middle line:10%
While children laugh
about 400 times per day,

00:12:17.150 --> 00:12:19.580 align:middle line:10%
adults barely manage
to squeeze in one.

00:12:19.580 --> 00:12:22.050 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:12:22.050 --> 00:12:25.020 align:middle line:90%


00:12:25.020 --> 00:12:27.990 align:middle line:84%
>> Now again, with the being
an adult and less laughs,

00:12:27.990 --> 00:12:29.370 align:middle line:90%
less fun.

00:12:29.370 --> 00:12:31.960 align:middle line:84%
This truly sounds
like a problem.

00:12:31.960 --> 00:12:34.020 align:middle line:90%
But what are the solutions?

00:12:34.020 --> 00:12:37.500 align:middle line:10%
As we've seen in this series,
Amy Cuddy, social psychologist,

00:12:37.500 --> 00:12:40.740 align:middle line:10%
shows that two minutes
of arms above head

00:12:40.740 --> 00:12:43.050 align:middle line:10%
changes your whole
chemistry so you can feel

00:12:43.050 --> 00:12:45.660 align:middle line:10%
more confident in the moment.

00:12:45.660 --> 00:12:49.560 align:middle line:84%
Smiling in the mirror
changes your chemistry,

00:12:49.560 --> 00:12:52.590 align:middle line:84%
so you can actually feel
happier in the moment.

00:12:52.590 --> 00:12:55.320 align:middle line:84%
And sure enough, laughing
for a few minutes

00:12:55.320 --> 00:12:57.270 align:middle line:84%
changes your
chemistry and puts you

00:12:57.270 --> 00:12:59.790 align:middle line:84%
into an altered state to
where you're approaching

00:12:59.790 --> 00:13:02.340 align:middle line:90%
the now moment differently.

00:13:02.340 --> 00:13:04.950 align:middle line:84%
This is truly one
of the best ways

00:13:04.950 --> 00:13:08.550 align:middle line:84%
to hack our emotional state
with the intelligent use

00:13:08.550 --> 00:13:10.530 align:middle line:90%
of our body.

00:13:10.530 --> 00:13:14.340 align:middle line:10%
Plato said, "our children,
from their earliest years,

00:13:14.340 --> 00:13:18.300 align:middle line:10%
must take part in all the
more lawful forms of play.

00:13:18.300 --> 00:13:21.520 align:middle line:10%
For if they are not surrounded
with such an atmosphere,

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:24.360 align:middle line:10%
they can never grow up
to be well conducted

00:13:24.360 --> 00:13:28.060 align:middle line:10%
and virtuous citizens."

00:13:28.060 --> 00:13:32.060 align:middle line:10%
So play is truly
good for society.

00:13:32.060 --> 00:13:35.560 align:middle line:84%
But why does it seem so
difficult to introduce play

00:13:35.560 --> 00:13:38.530 align:middle line:90%
into our lives as we age?

00:13:38.530 --> 00:13:42.450 align:middle line:84%
Why is it so difficult to have
fun in this kind of a rat race

00:13:42.450 --> 00:13:44.610 align:middle line:90%
that we seem to live in?

00:13:44.610 --> 00:13:46.860 align:middle line:84%
Well, that's the
discipline of it.

00:13:46.860 --> 00:13:50.100 align:middle line:84%
This is the path of
our human potential.

00:13:50.100 --> 00:13:51.990 align:middle line:84%
It's not going to
be handed to us.

00:13:51.990 --> 00:13:53.910 align:middle line:90%
We need to work on it.

00:13:53.910 --> 00:13:58.080 align:middle line:84%
It's a challenge that's
beckoning us to meet it halfway

00:13:58.080 --> 00:14:01.590 align:middle line:84%
so we can at least engage
with it, learn from it.

00:14:01.590 --> 00:14:05.910 align:middle line:84%
Because being able to
endogenously or self-produce

00:14:05.910 --> 00:14:09.390 align:middle line:84%
a state of play in the most
unlikely and even difficult

00:14:09.390 --> 00:14:14.100 align:middle line:84%
circumstances is truly
a superhuman skill.

00:14:14.100 --> 00:14:17.580 align:middle line:84%
But the paradox is,
laughter, and even smiling,

00:14:17.580 --> 00:14:20.620 align:middle line:84%
is not appropriate
in all situations.

00:14:20.620 --> 00:14:26.040 align:middle line:84%
But rising to the occasion
of the challenge always is.

00:14:26.040 --> 00:14:28.950 align:middle line:84%
One of the best ways to enter
into the parts of our mind

00:14:28.950 --> 00:14:32.340 align:middle line:84%
that need laughter
the most, we probably

00:14:32.340 --> 00:14:35.880 align:middle line:84%
have to at least acknowledge,
if not find beauty,

00:14:35.880 --> 00:14:39.660 align:middle line:84%
in the darkness of the mind,
those dark corners that

00:14:39.660 --> 00:14:43.110 align:middle line:84%
hold all of our resistance
and all of our fears

00:14:43.110 --> 00:14:47.140 align:middle line:84%
in order to start working
on that superhuman skill.

00:14:47.140 --> 00:14:49.680 align:middle line:84%
And one of the best ways
to work on this skill

00:14:49.680 --> 00:14:51.390 align:middle line:90%
is by starting small.

00:14:51.390 --> 00:14:54.690 align:middle line:84%
I suggest turning your daily
chores, the things you'd rather

00:14:54.690 --> 00:14:57.240 align:middle line:84%
not be doing, into
an opportunity

00:14:57.240 --> 00:15:01.470 align:middle line:84%
to introduce play into
a moment of service.

00:15:01.470 --> 00:15:04.050 align:middle line:84%
Take, for instance,
what Alan Watts

00:15:04.050 --> 00:15:07.185 align:middle line:84%
has to say about chores
in his essential lectures.

00:15:07.185 --> 00:15:10.010 align:middle line:90%


00:15:10.010 --> 00:15:14.150 align:middle line:10%
>> The art of washing dishes is
that you only have to wash one

00:15:14.150 --> 00:15:16.730 align:middle line:10%
at a time.

00:15:16.730 --> 00:15:18.440 align:middle line:10%
If you're doing
it day after day,

00:15:18.440 --> 00:15:21.320 align:middle line:10%
you have in your mind's
eye an enormous stack

00:15:21.320 --> 00:15:25.040 align:middle line:10%
of filthy dishes, which you
have washed up in years past,

00:15:25.040 --> 00:15:29.120 align:middle line:10%
and an enormous stack of filthy
dishes, which you will wash up

00:15:29.120 --> 00:15:31.940 align:middle line:10%
in years future.

00:15:31.940 --> 00:15:36.133 align:middle line:10%
But if you bring in your mind
to the state of reality which

00:15:36.133 --> 00:15:40.270 align:middle line:10%
is, as I've pointed out to you,
only now, this is where we are.

00:15:40.270 --> 00:15:42.490 align:middle line:10%
There is only now.

00:15:42.490 --> 00:15:45.130 align:middle line:10%
You only have to wash one dish.

00:15:45.130 --> 00:15:47.070 align:middle line:10%
It's the only dish you'll
ever have to watch.

00:15:47.070 --> 00:15:48.580 align:middle line:10%
This one.

00:15:48.580 --> 00:15:50.110 align:middle line:10%
You ignore all the rest.

00:15:50.110 --> 00:15:53.380 align:middle line:10%
Because in reality, there is
no past and there is no future.

00:15:53.380 --> 00:15:54.490 align:middle line:10%
There is just now.

00:15:54.490 --> 00:15:56.260 align:middle line:10%
So you wash this one.

00:15:56.260 --> 00:16:00.160 align:middle line:10%
And instead of thinking,
have I got it really clean,

00:16:00.160 --> 00:16:04.300 align:middle line:10%
is you turn the cleaning
movement into a dance.

00:16:04.300 --> 00:16:06.130 align:middle line:10%
And you dig that.

00:16:06.130 --> 00:16:08.680 align:middle line:10%
And you swing that
plate around and you let

00:16:08.680 --> 00:16:10.360 align:middle line:10%
the rinsing water go over it.

00:16:10.360 --> 00:16:12.960 align:middle line:10%
You put it off in the rack.

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:13.760 align:middle line:10%
Crazy.

00:16:13.760 --> 00:16:14.230 align:middle line:10%
See?

00:16:14.230 --> 00:16:15.030 align:middle line:10%
Take the next one.

00:16:15.030 --> 00:16:17.700 align:middle line:10%


00:16:17.700 --> 00:16:20.920 align:middle line:10%
And you get this
rhythm going, see?

00:16:20.920 --> 00:16:25.570 align:middle line:10%
And you're not under
compulsion all the time.

00:16:25.570 --> 00:16:28.270 align:middle line:90%
>> Now just imagine that.

00:16:28.270 --> 00:16:32.710 align:middle line:84%
How Alan Watts was describing
the only dish you're washing

00:16:32.710 --> 00:16:34.600 align:middle line:90%
is the one in the moment.

00:16:34.600 --> 00:16:38.870 align:middle line:84%
Now expand that out to any other
chore, difficult situations.

00:16:38.870 --> 00:16:44.080 align:middle line:84%
Imagine having the skill to
be able to introduce play

00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:46.540 align:middle line:84%
into the things that
you never imagined

00:16:46.540 --> 00:16:50.200 align:middle line:84%
should have a playful
air about them.

00:16:50.200 --> 00:16:54.340 align:middle line:84%
And remember that there's
something about play that

00:16:54.340 --> 00:16:57.130 align:middle line:84%
puts you more into the moment,
because the only moment

00:16:57.130 --> 00:16:59.830 align:middle line:84%
that truly matters,
like Alan Watts said,

00:16:59.830 --> 00:17:02.530 align:middle line:90%
is this one, the one right here.

00:17:02.530 --> 00:17:05.470 align:middle line:84%
Now imagine a figure skater
going up for a triple Lutz,

00:17:05.470 --> 00:17:09.910 align:middle line:84%
one of the most difficult moves,
and having to land and continue

00:17:09.910 --> 00:17:12.010 align:middle line:90%
skating away gracefully.

00:17:12.010 --> 00:17:14.290 align:middle line:84%
That's a very
challenging moment.

00:17:14.290 --> 00:17:17.630 align:middle line:84%
But what is the best
way to approach it?

00:17:17.630 --> 00:17:22.270 align:middle line:84%
It's not by stressing yourself
out trying to overly manage

00:17:22.270 --> 00:17:23.680 align:middle line:90%
that situation.

00:17:23.680 --> 00:17:26.500 align:middle line:84%
It's a balance between
management and trusting

00:17:26.500 --> 00:17:28.292 align:middle line:84%
in the process,
trusting the fact

00:17:28.292 --> 00:17:29.500 align:middle line:90%
that you've been here before.

00:17:29.500 --> 00:17:31.770 align:middle line:90%
You've done this before.

00:17:31.770 --> 00:17:34.930 align:middle line:84%
The really most important
moment is the one

00:17:34.930 --> 00:17:38.080 align:middle line:90%
right here and right now.

00:17:38.080 --> 00:17:40.190 align:middle line:84%
Now there's this
guy, Marquese Scott,

00:17:40.190 --> 00:17:43.850 align:middle line:84%
